Greenery everywhere you look.
It has so many nice features, from a playground to barbeque grills, a number of clubhouses, a baseball field complete with  bleachers and a hot dog stand. There's the swimming pools too!!

<Review>Was looking forward to checking out this restaurant, since I'm a fan of ayce kbbq. I was pretty disappointed! While the price was wallet friendly, the food and service disappointed me big time! First the meat - normal selections you would expect at an ayce kbbq so nothing special here to talk about. The extras were lacking - like there was NO lettuce!  The self serve bar was tiny and the fruits were from a can and had no fruit taste!  Second the service - the limited staff was definitely short on people so we had to wait long for the meat to come out. I sympathize with them but blame the management for it.  Over all, didn't really enjoy the experience and would NOT come back.  This is a shame since this branch is closer to me than driving out to Korea town.  Oh well, gotta go where the good food is!</Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOQNxgb7jifMvKrWbu2hwtfknINc2TsqqC8uiN0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures>< Resp>

< user_name>
Nick Wong</user_name>
< UserId.>
101808260364825895736<//UserId.>
< text>
This is the place when people want to spend minimum money for AYCE Korean BBQ in local area. It only costs $19.99 per person to get a different kind of meat and seafood. I love to eat beef belly, rib fingers, and pork belly because they have good quality.  Also, it has mini salad bar which I love to grab tofu, fish cakes as much as I want. The service here is great, and food always cone out fast as well.  Also, beer is not expensive here for a mud size so next time I may order one as well.

It is very good place for 2 or more people to come here for BBQ because it has good environment, good quality of meat, and services.< /text>

<Date>1514315129558</Date>< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< text>
Went there as part of an Christmas Office party, where our group was distributed to several tables.  The place is clean, well-designed and brightly lit, upstairs in a somewhat shabby multi-use complex.  Tables typically seat 4 around a stainless grill at the center of the table, where you cook your own meat selections.

You order meats from a long menu -- including marinated beef, pork and chicken as well as unmarinated selections like steak, bacon ("pork bellies") and shrimp.  The staff will deliver up to three meat choices at a time to the table and you share.  Standard tableware are chopsticks and a single steel tong to be used in common to turn the meat.  There's a self-serve salad bar where you can also get some grillable accompaniments.

The grill surface is stainless steel and the staff will lift it off and replace it with a clean unit after your first round of meats.  There's a button on the table to summon a server when you are ready to order a second round of meats.  Theoretically, it is all you can eat, but two rounds was all we could manage.

This was my first experience with Korean BBQ and I think the newbie would want someone more experienced along for a first ride.  How satisfied you are is likely to vary with how successful you are in selecting meats and managing the cooking process and the traditional Korean condiments.  As simple as it is -- and there's nothing complicated about laying meat on the grill and turning it over when it appears to be done -- you will want some reassuring instruction from your companions.  The staff may be used to instructing newcomers -- I don't know because we had some experienced diners among us.  Service, as far as bringing meat and clearing the table, was efficient but not particular friendly or interactive -- that might not be case if you were not part of a large office party as i was.

The apparent quality of meat was very high.  I found the marinated beef especially tasty.  I am not sure I like sharing my table with a very hot grill, but that's necessary to the experience i suppose.  Other people i know said Honey Pig is as good as it gets in the Korean BBQ category.

Pricing seemed fair.  Standard gratuities are added to the bill.<//text>

1< /rating>
<Text>The atmosphere in the restaurant is perfect. Nice music and clean table wares. Service is average. BUT the star of any restaurant has to be the food which, at Honey Pig 2.0, is what I find very lacking in taste and quality. While the price tag seems pretty good for an average Korean barbecue restaurant, the quality is just not there.
First, let's start with the sides because that is what you will have to walk up and get it yourself in a buffet style which is fine. There are typical Korean sides such as kimchi, rice, mash potatoes, etc. what strikes me the most is the fried chicken which is stone cold. Kimchi tastes like it is bought from a store that comes in a plastic jar container.
Moving on to the meat which is very lacking in consistency. Brisket sometimes come with extreme amount of fat and no fat at all. Beef short ribs are very tough like rubber. Beef galbi came in a very strange condition. The beef itself is charred and seems like it has been partially cooked once before it was served.
Overall, the restaurant fails to highlight the most important thing, the food.</Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Resp>
None< /Resp>

<user>112986760179392746551< /user><user_name>Daniel Yu<//user_name><time>1507957755396< /time>< rating>
5<//rating>
<Text>Went during lunch time on Friday. The service was prompt and attentive. Refills were prompt, food came out quickly, the dishes were nice and clean, the side dish bar was nice and well stocked.

Best part? The pork belly, the marinated pork belly was delicious and full of flavor, the kalbi was boneless and prebbq'd lightly so it wouldn't take forever to cook on the hot plate.

Also, unlike most KBBQ places, this place actually turns on the hood, so that the place isn't smoky and you don't end up smelling like KBBQ when you're done. This is how it's supposed to be done, the other KBBQ places could most definitely learn a thing or two from this place!<//Text>< Pictures>

<Date>1515090712960<//Date><rating>5< /rating>< Review>
Ultimate Air Conditioning and Erez are amazing! After numerous unprofessional or overpriced estimators from various companies we choose Ultimate Air Conditioning to revamp our heating and A/C work done improperly by another contractor in 2011. We were referred to Erez by an Engineer friend in December, 2017 who told us that Ultimate Air Condition had a very reputable reputation for honesty and hard work. Not the cheapest and certainly not the most expensive. Just Fair pricing for intelligent, well thought out hard work.

Erez promptly arrived for his estimate and gave us the confidence in his ability do do the job. He came up with better alternate designs which even the largest corporate estimators missed. Many HVAC companies have little interest in smaller jobs or use scare tactics to convince you they are your heroes. Erez and his crew arrived on time with email and text notifications detailing estimated arrival times. Even signing the digital contract to commence work was convenient.

Approximately a two and a half day job, Erez neatly installed the new duct work for more even distribution and came back to make any necessary adjustments as needed. Erez and crew are polite, very hard working and professional. He was also very helpful in finding a solution when it was discovered that copper piping was in the way of a new duct that needed to be installed. They always swept up and left the construction debris cleaned up at the end of each day. They truly went above and beyond.

I typically never pay for a job until completed, but in this case when a return air box being built offsite was delayed a couple of days due to the Holiday, I still paid in full once the main job was completed. That is the level of trust which I placed in Erez. There are many "hit and run" companies which overcharge or never come back when there are issues. We have renovated dozens of homes throughout the years and have nightmare stories with other installers. Erez and Ultimate Air always returned when stated to complete the job.

Whether zoning, or installing complete new systems, Ultimate Air Condition is the go-to company recommended by many Realtors and satisfied customers. With neat installation, fair pricing and professionalism, my wife and I absolutely recommend Ultimate Air Conditioning.<//Review>

This includes workers in the office without masks and workers cleaning the inside of cars without masks. I mentioned this to the Assistant Manager during my last visit. <text>As an El Monte resident, I cannot believe I had not discovered this place before!

The service is adorable! It's family-oriented and has a very homely feeling. If you are a regular, the staff will recognize you and will converse with you about how you're doing, what you're up to, etc.

The food is great for an affordable price. It's a great deal deal here. Probably one of the best breakfast spots in El Monte.

If you're looking for a mom-and-pop joint in this area, I highly recommend this spot!<//text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO2NNLQwW8W9ST5rmUvlQ-sZh9l3dvfmNew56fQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNqsPPX9Rz0NRYsaxUcfKBo0-5P2Tk_CUyS1wDY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><userid>102726075962551189803</userid>< Rate>

Flo's is morethan just a coffee shop. It's your mom and pop's diner that serve good breakfast and lunch. I was looking for a go0d diner and ended up here to grab breakfast. I had coffee, a pancake, veggie omelette cheese with potatoes and buttered wheat bread. Their coffee taste good. Similarly, their veggie omelette taste good and of good portion. Pancake and wheat bread were soft, tasty and fluffy. Moreover, their potatoes were fresh and tasty. Staff were amiable, attentive, and professional and competent. Indoor atmosphere was very welcoming and typical mom/pops kinda vibe. Indoor seats were huge. No outdoor seating. Prices are fair and competitive. Ample of parking space. Overall, I highly recommend Flo's and will come back again.< /review>

A friend had told me that this was a great place for breakfast, so I thought of it yesterday when Peck Road was closed going north because a dead body had been found. So I had to go south. I also looked it up and it was #3 of 176 restaurants in El Monte. When I got there I thought it was closed because all their blinds were shut. But the sign said OPEN, so I went in. It's not crazy cheap, it's reasonable. I ordered the enchiladas verde with 2 eggs. It comes with either rice and beans or potatoes and beans for $8.95. Delicious. I'll try lunch next time because some of the sandwiches looked quite good. Menu said they come with a side. Parked right in the front of the door.< /review>

<Rate>4</Rate>< Review>
It was understaffed when we came in for breakfast for the first time and the waitress knew it.  She was an older lady but she was so nice and attentive when she could be and apologetic about the situation.  It happens, you know.

Anyway, we had a group of seven of us.  Our order was taken as quickly as it could be and the food came out quickly.  It was delicious.  Service was excellent and friendly.  The waffles are so yummy, light and crisp.  The Sour Dough French Toast was okay, a little overhyped.  Eating sour dough was not a good mix with the cinnamon sugar for me.

It seems Yelpers were very impressed with the coffee.  Even my group thought it was delicious.  It turned out to be nothing but a canister of Folgers Original.  LMAO!<//Review>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< Pics>
None<//Pics>
< review>
Great hole in the wall breakfast joint. I would say skip Denny's or Ihop and grab some food that Isn't chucked out of the kitchen like some soulless factory. If you're around Saturday or Sunday their menudo is great. A small plate is just under $6 and it was enough and delicious. Next, try their country fried steak with a side of tater tots and a biscuit and gravy. I really don't care for biscuits but I love to dip my tater tots in the gravy and its gooood with 4 o's.  If your just in the mood for some traditional eggs, sausage, bacon, hash-brown, and pancakes then this place  won't let you down. Finally just wanted to add that its one of those places that has been there forever, or at least it seems like that. You'll see the walls covered in pictures of El Monte from the early 1900's. This all just adds to the experience. With great service and great food at the right price what more can you ask for.<//review>

<UserId.>103648819521537886236<//UserId.><pics>None</pics>< Text>
Uniquely beautiful views of the city's high rises that I would appreciate a lot more if more people understood the need for dog leashes. My dog isn't friendly like that, he is a guard dog and at 9 way too old to change that now (not that I even would change it), so my ability to enjoy the park is somewhat ruined by the constant barrage of dogs running at him and owners calling them back anemically as I hold the dog such that no biting can occur.

Also the rocks look like the land is rich in mercury and the 5G tower makes your teeth hurt if the wind is blowing the right direction but if like me, you aren't worried about that, then it's a beautiful park.<//Text>

<Review>Great hill to walk around and see phenomenal views of the city and surrounding areas. The path up to the top of the hill is wide enough for many people to walk at the same time and still keep a good distance.
Besides the amazing views, I was surprised to find a ‚ÄúAltar for Healing‚Äù at the top of the hill.  A beautiful piece of art that allows one to write a note to a loved one who has passed. Having experienced the loss of a family member this year, I was so moved by whomever created this platform. Thank you for bringing our community a place of peace during such a chaotic and grief-filled year.< /Review><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMp77MXvTSYpjanDVBtvcn4XRtLlYn6NoduS6A=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO77bDC-mgAe7ieveyIAxleXet6bGtia4Na760=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>< response>

Beautiful place with incredible views, short hiking trails, and a lovely rope swing at the top. You're able to see pretty much a 360 view of San Francisco/the Bay Area, and it's truly beautiful. Such an amazing park for grand views of the city. Some of the trail can get pretty rocky with sheer drop offs but just take the high ones. This park is beautiful for watching the fog roll over the city in the evening or looking at spring flowers in the morning. Really anytime is the right time here. Also you can take your time or make it a quick trip. Five dog tails up!<//Review>

<Name>Michael H< /Name><Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
This is a great vista on the city, East Bay, western corridor out to the ocean through the Excelsior. Bernal Heights is one of the last areas in the city to be paved over. There are still little dirt road areas in general it has the real neighborhood feel to it. You can walk from Bernal Heights Park down to Cortland Street to enjoy the businesses there. All in all, good exercise and cool part of San Francisco.</Review>

Great spot to catch sunrise and sunset. Great spot to walk your dog. Great spot to come for a picnic. Great spot to read a book. < Review>
Best off leash dog park and city view: day or night. With easy parking!

I have been living in Bernal Heights for 5 years and I am yet to get bored of this place. I almost get goose bumps every time I come with my husky.

‚ú®You will:
- meet nice people
- meet nice dogs
- enjoy easy parking and stunning city views (360degrees)
- make your dog off-leash happy. Good recall is a must
- get inspired by local runners
- catch a swing ride (swing is down sometimes)
- might sight a coyote. Do not feed. Wild things need to stay wild
- take the best pics with the city scape

The sweeping views of San Francisco come courtesy to Bernal Heights Park‚Äôs hillside terrain. <Time>1556998275299</Time>< Text>
A great park. It offers great views of the city, especially the Mission. The park is also very large and has more than one peak, with a few trails that go through the grassy areas. The main peak has a large radio tower on it, and offers some of the best views. There is also a swing there, which is surprisingly sturdy and is fun to use.

Just be mindful of the weather, as it can be extremely windy. I've also seen coyotes here before, even on crowded days.</Text>

< text>
Day or night, dog or no dog, Bernal Heights Park is a great little city park where you can do as much or as little as you like. It is definitely worth a hike to the top for the 360¬∞ views and photo ops. Please be mindful that coyotes live here, so keep an eye put for them, especially at dawn/dusk/night and if your pup has come along. Enjoy!< /text>

<UserId.>117800561066090220938< /UserId.>< name>
Jonamir Ian Ventura</name>
<Time>1502594076224< /Time><Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
Great views of The City that rival that of Twin Peaks. I might just like Bernal better, but the drive up to Peaks is definitely more fun and windy. There's a really fun swing (one wooden and one tire)  at the top.

Nice jagged rocks make for some epic photo compositions. My friend and I didn't nearly explore everything, but we walked a circle around the main hill and really got to enjoy a panorama of the city. It was really refreshing to be so far removed from the hustle and bustle of San Francisco below.

Parking is really easy to find here. Highly recommended... Great hikes and a view to boot.<//Review>

San Francisco looks good from many angles but the mix of nature and city makes this place particularly beautiful. It offers lesser known but just as stunning views of San Francisco that are comparable to Twin Peaks and Hawk Hill.< /text>

We just happened to be staying nearby, and our breakfast waiter recommended seeing this park. I know lots of people will say there is a great view, but that is super under-selling it. I refuse to post a picture, because it won't do the view justice. The park is also small enough that it isn't a hike to get around it. Lots of friendly dogs playing fetch and whatnot, as well. Great spot to go in the morning after breakfast.< /Review>

< review>
I‚Äôm lucky I‚Äôm a neighborhood resident here and get to go up to this park any old time. This hill is steep but the views from the top are pretty incredible. It‚Äôs very rustic - trails are not super maintained, and there aren‚Äôt any amenities whatsoever. But it‚Äôs a community gathering place, wondrous lookout point, and excellent place to feel excited, recharged, and pensive. Bernal has a bit of an understated wild streak, and this hill is a core piece of the neighborhood culture.</review>

<userid>102111842540066804444<//userid>< name>
Jacob Varshavsky</name>
<Date>1559516425981<//Date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< Review>
One of my favorite places to go for a walk either by myself, with friends, with a romantic engagement, or with my best friend CK - my dog. üêï

This really is one of the less known gems and one of the seven main hills of San Francisco.

Quick guide:
Drivable up to almost the top. 2 small parking areas. Disabled parking available.
NO public restroom.
Great for walks.
Paved road with a few benches.
Trails for hiking.
Great views.
Dog friendly - expect lots of dogs.
Water fountain dog and human closer to the top
Tree swing on top
Alex Nieto memorial.
Total time to walk up and down from the bottom parking lot - around a half hour.
Suitable for good 2 hours of relaxed hillside hiking or quality time with your dog.

Verbose description

There is hardly any vegetation and very few large trees so your view is mostly unobstructed, on a clear day that is. The summit area is fenced off and houses some sort of a smaller radio tower but the area all around the fence is walkable. The public can enjoy the summit, the tower doesn't hog all of it.

There are many ways to access this park but the main way is a paved road at the end of Folsom Street. Follow it past Cesar Chavez a few blocks and it winds up the hill. The first stop you come to is a small parking lot of 4 spots and 1 disabled spot. From there, a closed for driving paved road goes into the park and the other road keeps going up the side of the hill and around it. You can drive further up and there is more parking, mostly street parking. One disabled parking spot is available on the top also. Lots of parking along the road. Access to the other side of the hill, Bernal Heights neighborhood, Bayshore, etc.

The paved road that is closed to cars leads up to the top parking lot also and continues up almost to the summit. To get to the very top you will have to hike up a little bit of gravel or dirt trails. There are plenty of trails available on the side of the hill and a large open space on the South Eastern slope.

This area is most frequented by dogs, dog walkers, dog owners, and people exercising. Be prepared to see many dogs of different kinds doing all sorts of doggy stuff. Another common sight is patents with young children.

There is also an open space at the level of top parking area. It features an impressive maze laid out of large stones, similar to the ones you may find at Land's End, MacLaren Park, and other Bay Area landmarks. There is a drinking fountain for humans and for dogs here. This area also has plenty of trash receptacles filled mainly with hundreds of pounds of bagged up dog poop. A great place to have a picnic. üòÇ

There are a few benches along the way so it is possible to sit down civilly, rest and enjoy the view.

There is a swing in the tree on the very top. If you aren't afraid of heights you can enjoy the view South and East of the hill while swinging pretty wide and high off the ground.

Mission is known as the sunniest part of town so it isn't rare to come up here and have open clear views of the city. However, it can get very windy so be mindful of that.

About half way up the paved road there is a community made and upkept memorial for Alex Nieto, a local resident who fell victim of police brutality. He was shot and killed by an SFPD officer on duty.

Please help keep this space clean and have fun!< /Review>

< UserId.>
111928922258475665063< /UserId.>
< name>
Davin Atkins</name>
<date>1567907257588<//date><Rate>5<//Rate>< text>
I was taken here by friends, and had no idea what it was. I climbed a trail I thought I would die on, and wondered if it could possibly be worth the effort.

At the top, I found a complete panoramic view of San Francisco that was absolutely awe inspiring. Remember that scene in Mr Roger's Neighborhood where they would go to the land of make believe, and you'd see this lovely little fake town? The view is like that, except its real. Like a real life tilt-shift image of the city.

The crowd was small, and I never felt crowded. The only thing I'd recommend is to be in ok shape, and wear good shoes. The slopes are steep, and the ground feels loose. Many good experiences in life have a feeling like you could possibly die if you trip, and this is one of them.</text>
< Pictures>
None</Pictures>

Great views of downtown San Francisco & the bay. Very easy hike from park entrance to summit via mostly paved road. Strollers & wheelchairs can approach the summit & reach a fantastic view of downtown. But access to the highest point is via a short but steep foot trail. No bathroom facilities.<//Review>

<UserId.>100909611794934646296< /UserId.>< Pics>
None<//Pics>
<review>It's a nice steep hill with big views of the city all around.  You can see Twin Peaks, Buena Vista Park, San Bruno Mountain, Hunter's Point Shipyard, Financial District, etc really well from the top.

Very popular spot for people to walk their dogs.  There is a paved road that circles around to the top, but there are also dirt trails all over the hillside.

There used to be a swing hanging from the tree at the top, but last time I was there, it had been removed.  I was sad to see this, because you could get really high and it was really exhilarating to swing way out above everything like that.

Also, I have seen a coyote there several times, which apparently frequents the area.</review>< time>
1534135426971< /time>

< Text>
I'm here at least 3-4 times a week for a wonderful off-leash dog walk to the top. It's always full of friendly people and well behaved dogs. Watching the seasonal paintings on the Bernal rock change is always fun for me. My only caution is that a coyote lives here that can be seen at any time throughout the day. So it's best not to let your dog stray too far.</Text>

< user_name>
Sarah L< /user_name>
<userid>102096467164348766344<//userid>< Rate>
4<//Rate>
< review>
What an amazing view of the city and surrounding neighborhoods. In all the years that I've come to visit San Francisco, I have yet to visit this look out point. On a clear day, you can see as far as the Bay bridge and Golden Gate Bridges. You can see the skyline of downtown and parts of the East Bay.

There's an access road to the top (there's a swing up there) and a dirt trail that wraps around the other side of the hill. Take both for a view from all sides of the park. Dogs off leash everywhere! And an adjacent hill with trails and blooming yellow flowers.</review>

< review>
Great place to enjoy the veiws of the whole city. It has great 360 degree veiws with clear days you can see for miles. This place is dog and kid friendly. Also, if you go a short distance there are a lot of places to eat before and after you come here. There is a nice single swing near the top too. You can get a good hike going around the park. On certain parts, you will need to have good footing but it is worth it. Overall, a great place to go.< /review>

< username>
K L< /username>
< time>
1475366176387<//time>
< rating>
4</rating>
< text>
Views of San Francisco are not quite as stunning as from Twin Peaks,  but Bernal Heights is more fun since there are trails that allow you to walk up the hill without the risk of getting hit by a car. It's about a mile walk from the 24th Street BART station. Also, the weather here tends to be sunnier and less windy.</text>

<UserId.>101661351205921196957< /UserId.><name>Brandon Agranovich< /name><Time>1471816720433<//Time><rate>5<//rate>< review>
I come to Bernal Heights every weekend and it never get's old. I definitely wouldn't classify it as a "hike" per se, but it's more intense than you're average uphill walk (depending on if you take the road or one of the many dirt paths).
It's a great place to:
- see an amazing panoramic view of the city
- catch a sunset
- walk your dog
- sit and talk with a friend
- meditate / do yoga with a view

Check it out! Note: in the summer/dry season.. Bernal get's very dry!! After the wet season, Bernal is super green and is a bit prettier (looks like the Shire from Lord of the Rings)<//review>
